{{Infobox newspaper | name = Minggu Pagi | school = | logo = | logo_size = | logo_alt = | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | motto = "Mingguan Enteng Berisi" | type = | format = [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|Tabloid]] | owner = <!-- or |owners= --> | founder = <!-- or |founders= --> | publisher = | president = | editor = | chiefeditor = | depeditor = | assoceditor = | maneditor = | generalmanager = | newseditor = | managingeditordesign = | dirinteractive = | campuseditor = | campuschief = | metroeditor = | metrochief = | opeditor = | sportseditor = | photoeditor = | staff = | foundation = {{start date and age|1948|12|}} <!-- or |launched= --> <!-- Use: {{start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | political = | language = Indonesian | ceased publication = | relaunched = | headquarters = Jl. P. Mangkubumi No. 40-46 | publishing_city = [[Yogyakarta]] | publishing_country = [[Indonesia]] | circulation = | circulation_date = | circulation_ref = | readership = | sister newspapers = | ISSN = | oclc = | RNI = | website = | free = }} '''''Minggu Pagi''''' (Indonesian for ''Sunday Morning'') is an Indonesian general interest weekly published by the [[Yogyakarta]]-based [[Kedaulatan Rakyat|Kedaulatan Rakyat Group]]. It began in 1948 as a magazine, switching to the [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid format]] in the 1980s.
==History== [[File:Minggu Pagi 6.45 (7 February 1954) cover.jpg|thumb|Cover of the ''Minggu Pagi'' magazine (7 February 1954), featuring the actress [[Lies Noor]]]] ''Minggu Pagi'' was established as a magazine in the central [[Java]]n city of [[Yogyakarta]] on 7 December 1948 by M. Wonohito and H. Samawi; the former was the editor in chief of the newspaper ''[[Kedaulatan Rakyat]]''.{{Sfn|Swift|1989|p=170}}{{sfn|Ministry of Education, Minggu Pagi}} Afterwards, the magazine did not publish again until 1950. The issues published through early 1951 were listed as Volume&nbsp;2. In April 1953 ''Minggu Pagi'' jumped from Volume&nbsp;4 to Volume&nbsp;6, thus bringing the number of volumes in-line with the years since the magazine was established.{{sfn|Kratz|1988|p=827}}
During a period of [[hyperinflation]] in [[Economic_history_of_Indonesia#Sukarno_presidency|the early 1960s]], ''Minggu Pagi'' ceased publication as a standalone magazine. It was reduced to eight pages and included as a supplemental with the newspaper ''Kedaulatan Rakyat''; as a result, the magazine's subscribers were required to pay extra for the newspaper. As the economy improved in the 1970s, ''Minggu Pagi'' was again issued as a stand-alone publication.{{sfn|Ministry of Education, Minggu Pagi}} It ultimately migrated to the [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid format]] in the 1980s.{{sfn|USIS|1992|p=77}}
In 1992 the [[United States Information Service]] described ''Minggu Pagi'', which by then consisted of twelve pages, as one of the oldest extant press publications in Indonesia.{{sfn|USIS|1992|p=77}} At this time it was one of several media published by [[Kedaulatan Rakyat|Kedaulatan Rakyat Group]], together with the newspaper ''[[Kedaulatan Rakyat]]'', the children's magazine ''Gatotkaca'', and the [[Javanese language|Javanese-language]] magazine ''Mekar Sari''.{{sfn|USIS|1992|p=46}}
==Contents== In its early years, ''Minggu Pagi'' included articles on a variety of topics, including science, film, traditional culture, tourism, and sports. It also included space for literary works, primarily short stories. Among short story writers and other authors, the magazine was seen as providing an alternative space for publication, one accessible to those who had not yet been recognized by the Jakarta-based "rulers"<!--''penguasa'' in the original--> of the Indonesian literary canon.{{sfn|Ministry of Education, Minggu Pagi}} Given this opportunity, as well as the honorariums paid to authors, ''Minggu Pagi'' soon became a popular medium in which local writers could publish their works.{{sfn|Derks|2002|p=333}}
In the 1950s, the Indonesian author {{Interlanguage link multi|Nasjah Djamin|id}} described ''Minggu Pagi'', as a "cesspool", a descriptor that the academic Will Derks characterises as "embracing the low status and insignificance [the magazine] might have had in the eyes of scholars and critics".{{sfn|Derks|2002|p=333}} Nevertheless, by 1988 more than four hundred writers had contributed their literary works to the magazine and its successor. These included [[Motinggo Busye]], {{Interlanguage link multi|Satyagraha Hoerip|id}}, [[Rendra]], [[Bakri Siregar]], and Djamin, who published his novel ''Hilanglah Si Anak Hilang'' in ''Minggu Pagi'' between 1960 and 1961 on request of the editors.{{efn|The novel was published in Volume 13, issues 39–42 {{harv|Kratz|1988|p=158}}.}}{{sfn|Derks|2002|p=333}}{{sfn|Kratz|1988|pp=158, 862–864}}
In the 1990s, ''Minggu Pagi'' had a column on sexuality, "Liku-Lika Seksualitas", managed by a "Dr. Rosi".{{sfn|Budiman|2000|p=55}} It also regularly featured information on miraculous healing, sacred sites, and invulnerability practices.{{Sfn|Browne|1999|p=90}}
